<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1881-10-28T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1881-10-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="184" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d184">
                    <head>No. 183.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Blaine</persName>
                            to Mr. <persName type="to">Angell</persName></hi>.</head>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1881-10-28"><hi rend="italic">October</hi> 28,
                            1881</date>.</dateline>
                        <seg rendition="#left">No. 128.]</seg></opener>
                    <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to acknowledge the receipt of your
                        dispatch No. 204, of August 28 last, reporting the decision of the Chinese
                        Government in the matter of the Yang-tse junk regulations, and to say that,
                        in view of all the facts now before it, the Department is not supposed to
                        question the justice of the conclusion reached by that government.</p>
                    <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                    <closer><signed>JAMES G. BLAINE.</signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>